Step 1: Calculate Quick Assets. We exclude inventory from current assets. The components are:
• Cash on Hand = 4,303,451.63  
• Bank Deposits = 2,938,804.13  
• Interest Receivable = 8,592.81  
• Accounts Receivable = 1,502,354.84  

Adding these up:  
Quick Assets = 4,303,451.63 + 2,938,804.13 + 8,592.81 + 1,502,354.84 = 8,753,203.41  

Step 2: Identify Current Liabilities. From the balance sheet, Total Current Liabilities = 728,279.50  

Step 3: Compute the Quick Ratio.  
Quick Ratio = Quick Assets / Current Liabilities  
= 8,753,203.41 / 728,279.50 ≈ 12.02  

Step 4: Compute the Net Profit Margin.  
From the income statement:  
• Net Profit = 1,095,371.35  
• Total Revenue = 5,565,589.48  

Net Profit Margin = (Net Profit / Total Revenue) × 100  
= (1,095,371.35 / 5,565,589.48) × 100 ≈ 19.68%  

Thus, the solution is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Quick Ratio": "12.02",
    "Net Profit Margin": "19.68%"
  }
}
